  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date federal contract obligations in Louisiana total $3.6B across 18,029 awards, with an average award size of $198K. Obligations fell 24.8% year over year. The largest single sector is Ship Building and Repairing at $1.6B, driven by major prime contractors such as BOLLINGER SHIPYARDS LOCKPORT, L.L.C. at $1.3B. Department-level concentration is high: the Department of Homeland Security obligated $1.5B and the Department of Defense obligated $1.4B, together accounting for the bulk of state spending. Other sizable agency obligors include the Department of Energy at $255M and the Department of Agriculture at $92.1M. Beyond shipbuilding, Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction and Facilities Support Services represent the next-largest industry commitments at $451M and $385M respectively. Fiscal-year totals shown are partial (fiscal year to date) and reflect obligations rather than final spending.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How much did obligations change year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 24.8% year over year. Total obligations for FY2026 to date are $3.6B compared with prior fiscal-year totals such as $4.8B in FY25 and $4.5B in FY23. The drop is evident against recent peaks and contributes to a lower average award size context despite 18,029 awards at $198K each on average."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and industries drive Louisiana contracting?",
        "body": "The Department of Homeland Security and the Department of Defense are the largest buyers at $1.5B and $1.4B respectively. Ship Building and Repairing dominates by industry at $1.6B, supported by top vendors such as BOLLINGER SHIPYARDS LOCKPORT, L.L.C. at $1.3B and other major suppliers including STRATEGIC STORAGE PARTNERS, LLC. at $424M and PITTMAN-SEALEVEL, L.L.C. at $420M."
      }
    ]
  },
